REMARKS: MULTIPLE SPECIES.    Ring-billed Gull (Larus delawarensis), Herring Gull (Larus argentatus)        5 gulls struck on take-off run. Per Delta mechanics: damage to 3 fan blades in engine #2 and acoustic panel on engine #1, cost of repairs $270,000, and cost of labor $4000. Runway 3L was closed for 90 minutes for clean up. Four images uploaded to report. Per Delta, the aircraft rejected take-off just before V1 and came to a full stop 1000' from the end of the runway. Pilot reported seeing 30-50 large birds on the runway.  A321-211, Engine Manufacturer CFM INTL Classification Standard Engine Model CFM56-5B3/3. FOUR PHOTOS
COMMENTS: CHANGED DAMAGE TO SUBSTANTIAL DUE TO PHOTO OF ENGINE BLADES

REMARKS: DTW to LAS flght; arcrft dvrtd with emrgncy to MSP. Flght lnded 21:59 wth no nose gear steering prkng at Gte F13. Dmge vsble inside nose gear well to hydralic lines and cbling assmbly. Rmains torn apart, soaked in hyrdlc fluid; likly Snowy Owl.  Extent of damage is unknown. Bird struck at DTW; pilot stated he hit bird at rotation speed(Vr)and heard a 'thud.' Aircraft declared emergency and diverted to MSP. Unknown departure runway, arrived Runway12R
COMMENTS: REVISED EOF TO PREC LANDING INSTEAD OF Other: (Partial hydraulic failure)Emergency landing at KMSP two hours after take off due to loss of hydraulic pressure PER R DOLBEER

REMARKS: MOR Remarks: DAL1640 DEPARTED TO ATL AND WHEN AIRBORNE A LARGE BIRD WAS INGESTED IN THE ENGINE. HE SAID THE ENGINE WAS RUNNING NORMAL AFTER THE STRIKE BUT AS PRECAUTION DECLARED AN EMERGENCY AND RETURNED TO DTW. 181 SOULS ON BOARD, NEG HAZMAT, AND 4 HRS OF FUEL. LANDED WITHOUT INCIDENT  AFTER LANDING THE PILOT TOLD OPS THAT THEY HAD SHUT THE ENGINE DOWN AS A PRECAUTIONARY BUT AS OF NOW UNKNOWN IF ANY DAMAGE.  Other Remarks: Snowy Owl ingested upon rotation of departing aircraft. Engine number one destroyed. Right wing of owl found intact. Bird was otherwise completely annihilated. Aircraft landed safely.

Bird strike at touch down on Rwy 4L (strike occurred around the 4L aimpoint). 737-800, Engine Manufacturer CFM INTL Classification Standard Engine Model CFM56-7B27E/F During landing flair at touch down, in KDTW on RWY 04 L,  we experienced a bird strike from what appeared to be a small bird, hitting the forward cockpit window on the Captain side of the aircraft. No abnormal engine parameters or smell was experienced. We completed the landing and continued taxiing to our gate uneventfully. We reported the bird strike to ground control and our SWA operations in KDTW. The bird strike was written up in the logbook and I called dispatch and MX control. During our post flight inspection no additional bird strikes or damages were found. One small bird, unknown species struck windshield on landing. Smithsonian Wildlife/Species Identification: Red-winged blackbird (Agelaius phoeniceus)

REMARKS: A321-211, Engine Manufacturer CFM INTL Classification Standard Engine Model CFM56-5B3/3

Contract Maintenance for Delta Airlines notified Airport Operations that inbound Delta Airlines Flight 2556 reported a bird strike during takeoff roll at KDTW. The flight crew stated that they observed 12-15 birds during their takeoff roll and striking an unknown number of birds prior to rotation at a speed of 120 knots. During the post flight walk around at KRSW, the flight crew discovered evidence of a single bird strike on the aircraft's nose gear. Airport Operations collected snarge from the nose gear of the aircraft and sent it to the Smithsonian for identification. There was no effect on the flight and no damage to the aircraft.  KDTW Airfield Ops collected remains of 1 Ring-billed gull from 21R immediately following the report of the strike to ATC.  MOR: DAL2556 STRUCK A BIRD ON RWY 21L ON DEPARTURE.  WCAA RETRIEVED BIRD ON RWY 21L.  DAL2556 WILL CONTACT WCAA ONCE HE GETS TO HIS DESTINATION IF THERE IS ANY DAMAGES. A321-211, Engine Manufacturer CFM INTL Classification Standard Engine Model CFM56-5B3/3 Smithsonian Wildlife/Species Identification: White-headed gull complex (Larus spp)

bird strike on take off runway 22L.  No damage no injuries.  Bird fatality.  Bird corpse retrieved. NOTE: NUMBER STRUCK NOT REPORTED ASSUME 1.

Reported to have occurred on a 3 mile final for RWY 22R. Gull remains found at 22R/A3 turn off and assumed to fall out of landing gear of this aircraft due to offisite gull activity. Delta maintenance stated that there was bird strike evidence on the nose of the aircraft that they wiped off but also found snarge on the landing gear. Landing gear was sampled and came back as Pig. A separate strike was submitted for the pig as that species is not likely in this region (FAA strike report 2024-01-03-130403). No damage reported.  SECOND REPORT: Snarge collected from main right landing gear. Biologist's initially thought snarge was from a reported strike 3 miles from airport. Feral pigs are uncommon in this area and we did not find pig remains on the runway. Given the above information, this strike did not happen at DTW. FOUND KDTW. DAY Smithsonian Wildlife/Species Identification: Swine (pigs) (Sus scrofa) Smithsonian Wildlife Identification Comments: Pig dna in sample. No feather found in microscopic examination. Possible pig strike at another location, or food item from trash gull was eating? If more material is available we would be happy to re-examine. “Snarge on LG IDed by SFL as pig assumed to be from digestive system of herring gull.”

REMARKS: Fly EDV4654 from JFK to to DTW encounter a bird strike en-route. The bird struck above the landing/recog lights on the left wing. We are unable to identify when the incident occurred due to the time of the day. It was at night. We saw no bird nor heard any audible sound of a bird strike. After parking at the gate, a ramp agent approached us and notified us of the strike. MX was notified, MM01 was noted and a report was issues to ATC. To be on the safe side, it was written up as Flaps 45 degree and fully configured to land. Edit by KDTW: First, thank you to the pilot for submitting this so we could fill in our gaps of information since the crew was not available to talk to when we arrived. Thanks again! Information received from ATC on our end: ATCT reports possible bird strike on Rwy 21L (report is delayed by at least 15 minutes). Reported first 3000ft - Ops 313 set to drive Rwy 21L. Ops 335 to meet plane at gate. Crew is not with the plane upon arrival Ops 313 states nothing found on Rwy 21L, Rwy given back to tower at 21:38 Ops 335 did collect snarge on pilot side wing tip. Smithsonian Wildlife/Species Identification: White-throated sparrow (Zonotrichia albicollis)
bird strike on the runway.  no damage no injuries.  RWY 21L. NOTE: NUMBER STRUCK NOT REPORTED ASSUME 1.

Delta Maintenance advised DAL496 reported a bird strike on departure from DTW. ATL Ops met with the pilots who advised they struck approximately 3 birds on departure from Rwy 21R at DTW and they believe they ingested one bird in the #1 engine as well. The strike occurred as the aircraft was taking off from the runway at DTW with the nose gear off the ground but the main gear still on the pavement. Flight crew also reported striking a bird during approach to ATL (separate strike report). Delta Line Maintenance, the pilot, and  ATL Ops conducted a walk-around of the aircraft, a Boeing 737-900ER, N873DN, and observed 4 impact points: the lower left side of the nose, the left side fuselage just behind the nose, the leading edge of the left-side wing above the engine, and the #1 engine cell pylon. Snarge collected from each impact point. There was no visible damage to the aircraft, nor were there visible signs that an engine ingestion had occurred. SI ID= all 3 bags = Barn Swallow MOR: DAL496 DEPARTED RUNWAY 21R AND REPORTED A BIRD STRIKE TO LOCAL. NO ISSUES OR ASSISTANCE NEEDED.

2107 hrs-Inbound from KBDL Alert 2 issued - Aircraft DAL 1360 Boeing 717 - Compressor stall. Aircraft landed safely on RWY 21L. At the time of landing, it was unknown what caused the compressor stall. Compressor stall reported to have occurred at approximately 20 minutes from airport. Alert 2 terminated at 2127 and aircraft taxied to gate.  DTW airfield ops dispatch was later called on 3/16/20 by delta maintenance and was informed that bird remains were found in BOTH engines. Both engines may need to be replaced. EDIT: Ops specialist was initially told by Delta Maintenance that the sample was from a bird strike that happened after departure at KBDL. FAA strike report was first submitted to reflect such until speaking with C Cousineau (KBDL Wildlife Services) who gathered more information from Delta and relayed that information to KDTW wildlife biologist, S Creed. He stated he was told that ONE engine needed to be replaced. Selena spoke with Delta Maintenance at DTW and they said both engines were cleaned, inspected, and determined to be okay. So sorry about all of miscommunication on this one...Smithsonian Wildlife Identification Comments: Bag 1, engine 1, Common Goldeneye Bag 2, engine 2, Common Goldeneye

REMARKS: Airport Operations was notified of a bird strike on ExpressJet CRJ-900 (136EV). The aircraft landed on Runway 34 at 22:02L and was operating as ASQ5490 arriving from Detroit (KDTW). The strike occurred on the leading edge of the left wing. A full length runway inspection was completed by Airport Operations Coordinator with negative findings.     The pilot believed the strike may have occurred during the take-off run in Detroit, but he was not certain. The flight crew left the area before they could be questioned further. There was no effect on flight,  no damage to the aircraft and no injuries reported. USDA Wildlife Biologist Derek Colbert has been notified and the sample was sent to the Smithsonian for positive identification.

Evidence of a strike was found on the nose of the aircraft by airline maintenance personnel at KCLT.  The inbound flight crew was not available and it was initially unknown when/where this strike occurred.  A tissue sample was collected by KCLT Airport Operations personnel and sent to the Smithsonian for analysis.  KCLT Airport Wildlife Coordinator reviewed ATC communications with this aircraft for both KCLT and KDTW (originating airport) to determine if the flight crew reported anything.  Flight Crew did report seeing seagulls fly in front of their aircraft during takeoff run at KDTW, but did not report any wildlife during arrival and landing at KCLT.  KDTW Wildlife Biologist was contacted via email and informed that two bird carcasses were found on runway inspection after a reported strike, one carcass field ID as Savannah Sparrow and one as Horned Lark (strike reports #2017-5-1-140344 and 2017-5-1-135711 filed).  Remains found on this aircraft may or may not be related, pending species ID.  No damage was found on the aircraft.

REMARKS: Tower called and reported a possible bird  strike on RWY 22R. Aircraft is a B717 tail number N965AT flight number DAL 1580 that parked at gate A11. Ops 331 sent to the runway and Ops 314 sent to the aircraft. 1525 Ops 331 picked up 2 small birds from the runway unknown type. 1526 Ops 314 found nothing on aircraft. Wayne County Airport Authority later received an MOR stating that there was damage to the right wing of the aircraft as a result of the bird strike.  Airfield Ops management made follow up calls and sent follow up emails the following day to gather more information due to internal records not indicating that this was a damaging strike.  Airfield Ops Specialists stated that the initial call came through 20 minutes after the aircraft landed and that flight crew and maintenance were not available to speak to when they arrived at the gate. They stated that they inspected the aircraft and did not find any evidence of a bird strike or damage on the aircraft. Delta Maintenance stated that they had no records of that aircraft having any bird strikes in the past two days and that no aircraft were out for service due to a bird strike. Lastly, Delta Chief Pilot reached out to the pilot of that aircraft and confirmed that strike remains were found on the slat and that maintenance wiped the aircraft down and stated that there was NO damage to the slat. A barn swallow and a killdeer were found on inspection. Since the strike evidence was wiped off the aircraft before we could take a snarge sample, we can't be 100% sure on ID. Due to the number of Barn swallow strikes we have been receiving on RWY22R and the condition of the carcasses, we feel confident that the bird involved was the barn swallow rather than the killdeer. A separate and unrelated report for the killdeer will be filed. Right wing slat. MOR: DAL1580(N965AT) CONTACTED LNW FROM THE GATE THAT THEY HAD A BIRD STRIKE THAT RESULTED IN DAMAGE ON THE RIGHT WING. WCAA NOTIFIED.

Tower called and reported that SKW3725 a CRJ 900 N833SK struck a bird on FINAL and parked at gate B6. Pilot reported striking a possible seagull over the 22R approach at 1850Z and found a very small dent on the radome. Ops completed the airfield inspection and did not find bird remains on the runway. Wildlife Biologist met aircraft at the gate and advised that the bird struck the radome and that snarge had already been cleaned from the aircraft and disposed of. Further communication between the airline and airfield ops email confirmed damage to the right side of the radome. Per Chris Clem of Skywest Airlines, “We did receive relief from the manufacturer and it will need the skin replaced in 950 hours.” Minor damage. REMARKS: Pilot was not aware they struck a bird. At approximately 1010 hrs, airport biologist witnessed hawk remains on the departing end of 3L just after a couple of Delta aircrafts departed. Runway was closed for approximately 45 minutes to pick up bird debris and glass that was found near the bird remains. Ops believes a light was damaged on the aircraft based on the reflective glass and rubber and metal seal that was found. Strike occurred on the right side of the aircraft. Tower initially thought the aircraft was DL2812 en route to PBI, but their ops confirmed that no damage was found on walk around.  While completing a standard maintenance check of the aircraft upon arrival at KLGA, Delta Airlines maintenance representative found evidence of a possible bird strike to a light located under the aircrafts right wing.  He stated he spoke with a pilot from the inbound flight crew who stated they believed they struck a bird upon takeoff from KDTW.  The pilots were not present to provide additional information.  No sample was taken due to lack of attainable material.  On 5/20/22 DAL advised aircraft was not out of service, no damage, no cost.
COMMENTS: revised to struck/damaged lights with minor damage per remarks from Ops
